  abstract={This paper develops a dynamic model of the cognitive division of labour within firms. A continuum of questions arrive over time, and each must be assigned either to an expert or to a routine worker. Routine workers exploit codified knowledge by interpolating between previously solved problems, while experts possess tacit knowledge and can either address the current question or conduct research to create new knowledge point. The manager chooses whether to use experts to handle current issues (exploitation) or to invest in knowledge creation (exploration), taking into account the endogeneity of the knowledge base and the evolving organisational structure. The analysis shows that organisations initially expand by adding distant knowledge points, then transition to a refinement phase in which they fill gaps between existing anchors. We derive conditions under which organisational performance exhibits an S-shaped trajectory versus concave growth. Finally, we consider the adoption of artificial intelligence, distinguishing interpolation AI, which improves routine workers' precision, from application AI, which lowers the cost of expert operations. The two technologies have opposite comparative statics: improving interpolation raises the value of exploration and hastens routinisation, whereas lowering expert costs crowds out research. These results offer new predictions about the allocation of cognitive tasks and the impact of AI on organisational learning.},
