  notes = {LEVEL 5 FULL INTEGRATION. 5 Customer Journey Segments via LCA: Store-focused (22pct), Pragmatic online (31pct), Extensive online (16pct), Multiple touchpoint (15pct), Online-to-offline (16pct). COUNTERINTUITIVE FINDINGS: (1) Journey satisfaction most important for MTP (beta=0.58***) but not for store-focused (beta=0.11*), (2) Product satisfaction has ZERO effect for MTP (beta=0.01 NS) but crucial for store-focused (beta=0.40***), (3) NO showrooming segment found - webrooming more prevalent, (4) Mobile doesn't create new segment - concentrated in MTP (47pct).},
  abstract = {Based on anticipated utility theory and using latent class analyses on large-scale data from two samples of 2,443 and 2,649 journeys, the researchers identified five time-consistent segments: store-focused shoppers, pragmatic online shoppers, extensive online shoppers, multiple touchpoint shoppers, and online-to-offline shoppers. Journey satisfaction is most important for multiple touchpoint shoppers (beta=0.58), while product satisfaction matters more for store-focused (beta=0.40) and pragmatic online (beta=0.43) shoppers. Customer inspiration contributes to loyalty for store-focused, multiple touchpoint, and online-to-offline shoppers.}
